<BaseLayout title="The coursework, explained" active="task" description="The Macbeth coursework explained: the three set questions, AO1, AO2 and AO4, planning, thesis statements, structure, the drafting timeline and the integrity rules.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">Edexcel International GCSE English Literature &middot; Component 3: Literary Heritage</p>
      <h1>The coursework, explained</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        One essay on Macbeth, written over weeks with your annotated copy of the play open beside you.
        This page takes you from choosing a question to submitting a final draft, and is clear about the
        rules, because this piece must be entirely your own work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">The task</h2>
      <p>
        You write <strong>one essay on Macbeth</strong> for the Literary Heritage strand of the coursework
        component. It is open book, word-processed, with quotations referenced and any secondary sources
        acknowledged. It is marked out of 30, split equally across three assessment objectives:
      </p>
      <ul class="tick">
        <li><strong>AO1 (10 marks):</strong> close knowledge and understanding of the play, a critical style, and informed personal engagement. Your reading, argued in your voice.</li>
        <li><strong>AO2 (10 marks):</strong> analysis of the language, form and structure Shakespeare uses to create meaning and effect. For a play, form means <em>theatre</em>: soliloquy, staging, dramatic irony, verse and prose, what happens on stage and what is kept off it.</li>
        <li><strong>AO4 (10 marks):</strong> the relationship between the play and its contexts. Worth a full third of the mark, and the single objective students most often neglect.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Because context carries a third of the mark, it cannot sit in a paragraph of its own at the end.
        The strongest essays open each paragraph with a contextual angle and loop back to it in the
        analysis. There is more on this on the <a href="/context/">context page</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="questions">The questions</h2>
      <p class="small">Three set questions. Every one carries the instruction: <em>you must consider language, form and structure and refer to the context of the play in your answer.</em></p>
      <table class="sow">
        <thead><tr><th>Focus</th><th>Question</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Kingship</strong></td><td>Explore the theme of kingship in Macbeth.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Women</strong></td><td>Explore the presentation of women in Macbeth.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Masculinity</strong></td><td>To what extent do you agree that Macbeth is presented as a masculine character?</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        Choose the question whose evidence excites you most, then read its matching
        <a href="/themes/">theme section</a> and gather from the <a href="/quotations/">quotation bank</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="planning">Planning and structure</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li><strong>Interrogate the question.</strong> Put it in your own words and stake a position. &lsquo;To what extent&hellip;&rsquo; means you must weigh, not just illustrate.</li>
        <li><strong>Write a thesis statement.</strong> One or two sentences setting out your central argument, a map you can look back at to keep yourself on task.</li>
        <li><strong>Gather discriminating evidence.</strong> Short quotations from across the whole play, each carrying a method and a contextual angle you can actually develop.</li>
        <li><strong>Build three balanced paragraphs.</strong> Each AO carries ten marks, so each paragraph should give roughly equal weight to knowledge, to method, and to context.</li>
        <li><strong>Open with the big picture, then narrow.</strong> Set the play as a Jacobean tragedy, introduce your focus, then lay out your line of argument before the first quotation.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="box teach">
        <h3>Every paragraph, three moves</h3>
        <p>A contextualised topic sentence that frames the point through Shakespeare&rsquo;s world; well chosen evidence that gives you room for close analysis of language, form and structure; and a loop back to context that explores the &lsquo;why&rsquo; of his choices. Naming a device is labelling, not analysis: push every method to its effect on the audience.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="drafting">The drafting timeline</h2>
      <p>
        The work is submitted in stages: a first draft, a second draft, and a final submission, with
        feedback on the first two that you are expected to act on carefully. Your teacher sets the dates
        each year. Format the essay as required: typed, size 11 in a sensible font, the essay title set as
        your chosen question, your full name in the header, page numbers at the bottom left, and all teacher
        comments deleted before you resubmit.
      </p>

      <h2 id="integrity">The rules, and why there is no feedback tool here</h2>
      <p>
        This coursework is assessed under strict integrity rules. You sign a declaration that the work is
        your own, that you have referenced any sources and any artificial intelligence tools you used, and
        you understand that a false declaration is malpractice. Your teacher signs to say the work was
        completed without unacceptable assistance and that AI has not been used to mark it.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is why this site, unlike the exam sites in the Extended English family, carries
        <strong>no AI feedback tool</strong>. An automated marker would sit exactly where the rules say
        nothing automated should be. The site gives you knowledge, method and worked guidance; the thinking,
        the argument and the writing are yours, which is the whole point of coursework.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
